The vulnerability seems to be related to improper object lifetime management leading to memory corruption. Here's a simple example of how such a vulnerability could be exploited:

```cpp
#include <objc/objc.h>

@interface VulnerableObject : NSObject
@property (nonatomic, strong) id someProperty;
@end

@implementation VulnerableObject
@synthesize someProperty = _someProperty;

- (void)doSomething {
    // Allocate memory for someProperty but don't set it yet
    self.someProperty = nil;

    // Do some work that takes a long time
    [self performSelectorInBackground:@selector(longRunningTask)];

    // Set someProperty to point to malicious data
    self.someProperty = [[NSData alloc] initWithBytes:maliciousData length:sizeof(maliciousData)];
}

// longRunningTask method omitted for brevity

@end

int main() {
    VulnerableObject *obj = [[VulnerableObject alloc] init];
    [obj doSomething];

    // The object may still be alive when longRunningTask finishes, causing memory corruption
    // due to the malicious data being written to the incorrect location.
}
```

This example demonstrates a race condition where the object is allocated but not initialized before it is pointed to by `someProperty`. If the long-running task takes enough time, the object may still be alive when `someProperty` is updated with malicious data, resulting in memory corruption.

To fix this vulnerability, you should ensure that objects are properly initialized before they are used and manage their lifetimes carefully. In this case, you might want to use ARC or manually manage your memory to avoid these issues.

